<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="478" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1053,1258]" pageId="9" pageNumber="478">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,321,1125,1150]" pageId="9" pageNumber="478">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Distinguished from other genera in 
<taxonomicName box="[747,904,1125,1150]" class="Aves" family="Thamnophilidae" genus="Myrmorchilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="478" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[747,904,1125,1150]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="478">Myrmorchilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
clade by black streaked upperparts combined with black anterior underparts (males) or streaked black (females), black patch formed by wing coverts and bases of primaries, and black and rufous tails. Hallux short relative to tarsus length. Loudsongs structurally distinct. Tail “swings” over back unique in clade as is bromeliad-laden habitat. Ground nest differs from that of 
<taxonomicName box="[1257,1413,1233,1258]" class="Aves" family="Thamnophilidae" genus="Myrmophylax" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Passeriformes" pageId="9" pageNumber="478" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1257,1413,1233,1258]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="478">Myrmophylax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
